#. type: Plain text
#: ../../../../../doc/misc/message.texi:984
msgid "Whether to use the standard @acronym{OpenPGP} or @acronym{S/MIME} is beyond the scope of this documentation.  Actually, you can use one standard for one set of recipients and the other standard for different recipients (depending their preferences or capabilities)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../../../../../doc/misc/message.texi:994
msgid "In case you are not familiar with all those acronyms: The standard @acronym{OpenPGP} is also called @acronym{PGP} (Pretty Good Privacy).  The command line tools offered by @acronym{GnuPG} for @acronym{OpenPGP} are called @command{gpg} and @command{gpg2}, while the one for @acronym{S/MIME} is called @command{gpgsm}.  An alternative, but discouraged, tool for @acronym{S/MIME} is @command{openssl}.  To make matters worse, e-mail messages can be formed in two different ways with @acronym{OpenPGP}, namely @acronym{PGP} (RFC 1991/4880) and @acronym{PGP/MIME} (RFC 2015/3156)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../../../../../doc/misc/message.texi:1000
msgid "The good news, however, is the following: In GNU Emacs, Message supports all those variants, comes with reasonable defaults that can be customized according to your needs, and invokes the proper command line tools behind the scenes for encryption, decryption, as well as creation and verification of digital signatures."
